## Introducing Today's Project!

### What is Amazon VPC?

Amazon VPC (Virtual Private Cloud) is a service that enables you to create and manage a logically isolated network within AWS. It allows you to define your own IP address ranges, subnets, route tables, and security controls.

It is useful because it provides secure and flexible networking for AWS resources, allowing you to control traffic flow, isolate workloads, and build scalable cloud architectures that meet security and operational requirements.


### How I used Amazon VPC in this project

In today's project, I used Amazon VPC to create a VPC endpoint that enabled an EC2 instance in my public subnet to communicate with Amazon S3 without requiring internet access. I configured the endpoint, associated it with the appropriate route table, and verified that traffic to S3 was routed through the AWS network instead of an Internet Gateway. This demonstrated how VPC endpoints improve security and reduce dependency on public internet connectivity.


### One thing I didn't expect in this project was...

One thing I didn't expect in this project was that simply creating a VPC endpoint was not enough to enable access to Amazon S3. I also needed to associate the endpoint with the correct route table so that traffic destined for S3 would be routed through the endpoint. This highlighted how important route tables are in controlling network traffic within a VPC.


